Fabulous gazpacho - the best! I took it to a party and everyone raved about it. This was my first time making gazpacho and although it is a lot of chopping, it is totally worth it. The biggest difference was I reserved about a cup of chopped onion, cucumber and yellow pepper as well as a cup of diced tomatoes then pureed the rest in a blender and added the reserved veggies back to the soup at the end. Thanks to all of the amazing reviews that helped me modify the recipe for a double batch, here are the quantities I used: 2 eggs; 3/4 lb. chopped plum tomatoes; 2 yellow peppers; 2 cucumbers (one peeled on with skin); 1 large red onion; 1/4 cup good olive oil; Splash of basil oil; Juice of 2 lemons; 2 cups beef broth; 1/2 cup red wine vinegar; 1/2 cup fresh parsley; 2 tsp. dried oregano; 2 TBSP Worcestershire; Ground pepper to taste; 5 garlic cloves; Kosher salt; 1 46 oz. can Spicy V-8; 1/2 to 1 46 oz. can Tomato juice; 1 cup plain unseasoned breadcrumbs; 2 serrano chilies with seeds. Based on the review below I served it with an avocado cream: blend 1.5 to 2 Haas avocados with 1 spoonful plain yogurt or sour cream; juice of 1/2 lime; kosher salt to taste; ground pepper; 1/2 serrano chili; 3-4 chives; 2-3 basil leaves; splash of basil oil; 1/4 cup water plus more to reach desired thickness. Serve the avocado cream on the side and add a spoonful to each bowl of soup.

