This recipe is sublime. I'm posting my notes becase anyone who tries my gazpacho wants the recipe. V8 v. tomato juice. The only reason to use V8 is in the winter when the veggies arent good. In the summer, why spend all that time chopping the veggies if you cant appreciate their taste on their own without the pollution of the V8?! Peppers. Use yellow peppers. Adds another beautiful color. Olive oil. I always double this recipe but only use ¼ cup of good quality oil for the whole thing. Parsley. Always use fresh. Oregano. Use Greek or Spanish if you can find it. Adds greatly to the Med. flavor. Garlic. Five cloves for a double batch. Mash the egg finely with the garlic and salt. This is the brilliant part of this recipe. Lemon juice. Use freshly squeezed. I use one and ½ lemons for a double batch. Beef broth. Again, good quality. I use two cups for the double batch (with an extra tsp. of beef broth conentrate). Bread crumbs. Best quality, not seasoned&.remember, why bother polluting the taste of all your cutting and chopping?! Basil: When fresh is in season, I add some cut ribbons to each serving (the basil is not sorely missed if you dont have it). This really does hold well for about a week. Follow Cooks Notes plus mine, and youll be happy. [Cilantro doesnt belong in a true Spanish gazpacho. However, if you add some and a bunch of cold shrimp, youll have a Mexican shrimp cocktail.] [I've served this in a punch bowl on ice with bowls of salad shrimp, chopped avocado (tossed with lemon juice) and ribbons of basil for garnishes.] [When it's 30 below and you want to taste summer, this is your recipe, just use the V8 and buy the best veggies you can find.]

